NORMALISED EXTRACT:
1. Rule definition
- Replace numbers divisible by 3 with "fizz".
- Replace numbers divisible by 5 with "buzz".
- Replace numbers divisible by both 3 and 5 with "fizzbuzz".
- Counting proceeds incrementally from 1 upward; players or program output sequence.

2. Implementation logic
- Primary check order: check for divisibility by both 3 and 5 (i.e., 15) first to output "fizzbuzz", then check 3 then 5.
- Divisibility test: use integer modulus operator: n % k === 0.
- Loop bounds: start at 1 and continue to desired N (e.g., 100); inclusive upper bound N.
- Output format: sequential values separated by commas/spaces or one-per-line depending on consumer.

3. Variants and edge cases
- Additional divisibility rules: e.g., 7 or digits-containing rules (numbers containing digit 5 trigger buzz).
- Non-integer inputs: ignore or validate and throw error; canonical FizzBuzz is defined for positive integers.
- Very large N: ensure loop counter uses integer types that preserve exactness; in JS use Number but be aware of MAX_SAFE_INTEGER.

4. Performance and complexity
- Time complexity: O(N) with O(1) per iteration.
- Memory complexity: O(1) if streaming output; O(N) if accumulating results in memory.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS:
- Recommended implementation pattern:
  - For imperative languages: for (i = 1; i <= N; ++i) { if (i % 15 === 0) print('fizzbuzz'); else if (i % 3 === 0) print('fizz'); else if (i % 5 === 0) print('buzz'); else print(i); }
  - For functional languages: map over range 1..N and apply mapping function using modulus checks in same order.
- Testing recommendations:
  - Unit tests verifying outputs at known indices: 3 -> fizz, 5 -> buzz, 15 -> fizzbuzz, 1 -> 1.
  - Property-based tests: for any k divisible by 3 and not 5 -> fizz, divisible by 5 and not 3 -> buzz, divisible by 15 -> fizzbuzz.
- Edge-case handling: define behavior for 0, negative numbers, non-integers; typically either exclude or throw RangeError/TypeError.

